comments.body:
@daxian-dbw Because [it's apparently community best practice](https://github.com/PoshCode/PowerShellPracticeAndStyle/blob/master/Best-Practices/Building-Reusable-Tools.md#pure-01-use-native-powershell-where-possible).

Also, `::new()` is about as well-documented as `@().ForEach()` and `@().Where()` are.  If we're going to rely on it as the primary method of instancing objects, it ought to be much better documented.  It's only ever used in reference to user defined classes in the documentation.

@BrucePay Ok, so _yes_, there _is_ a reason that New-Object couldn't accept an actual data type instead of requiring a string representation of the data type.  I do see that with this:

```
PS > function Test-DataType ($DataType) { $DataType.NameSpace }
PS > Test-DataType ([int])
System
PS > Test-DataType [int]
PS >
```

@thezim Hm.  That is basically what I'm trying to do and it does not work for me via the command line or with VSCode's PowerShell module (VSCode 1.25.1, PS module 1.8.2).  Maybe something on my system is just not working correctly, however, because it does seem to work for my coworker.  And it does seem to work for me if I RDP to a server and run PowerShell there.  Looks like I will need to reset my environment completely and test it again.
